What happens when you type ‘google.com’ in your browser then you press enter 

Demystifying the Web: A Journey from Keystrokes to Pixels

Ever wonder what happens when you enter "https://www.google.com" into the address bar of your browser and press Enter? We'll dissect the complex dance of technologies and protocols that takes place in the background in this blog article. DNS queries, TCP/IP handshakes, firewalls, HTTPS/SSL encryption, load balancing, web servers, application servers, and databases are all involved in this journey.

DNS Request: Finding the Digital Address
Your browser asks, "Where is www.google.com?" as its initial query. This initiates a DNS (Domain Name System) lookup, akin to locating a number in a phone book. The browser looks for the IP address associated with the domain in order to connect to Google's servers.

TCP/IP: Establishing a Connection
Your browser establishes a TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) connection to Google's server by using the IP address as a guide. This involves several handshakes to ensure that a reliable data transmission connection is established between your browser and Google's ser

Firewall: Gatekeeper of Data
Your browser establishes a TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) connection to Google's server by using the IP address as a guide. This involves several handshakes to ensure that a reliable data transmission connection is established between your browser and Google's server.

HTTPS/SSL: Securing the Conversation
In the digital world of today, privacy is crucial. The connection between your browser and Google is often secured via HTTPS (Hypertext Transfer Protocol) with SSL (Secure Sockets Layer) or its more modern equivalent, TLS (Transport Layer Security). This ensures that the information transmitted is secure and kept confidential.

Load-Balancer: Distributing the Load
Load balancers are used by Google to effectively manage the massive volume of traffic flowing through its extensive infrastructure. They split up incoming requests among several servers to avoid overloading any one of them and to guarantee peak performance.

Web Server: Serving Web Pages
The destination is the web server, which houses the requested web page. After processing your request, the web server sends the required files back to your browser. This could include JavaScript, HTML, and CSS files for Google's homepage.

Application Server: Dynamic Magic
The web server and application server work together occasionally, particularly when dynamic material is involved. The application server sends the completed output back to the web server for transmission after processing server-side scripts, database queries, or other dynamic components.

Database: Behind-the-Scenes Data Storage
Large volumes of data are stored in a database for Google. This could include search results, user data, and other things. In response to your request, the application server interacts with the database to get or change data.

At the very end, all of these elements come together to produce Google's homepage loading smoothly on your browser. The web material we engage with on a daily basis is delivered by a complex dance of technologies that work together in a process that appears practically immediate to us.
